51
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:39,880
You might think at the least that the problem of the origin of life, how did life appear

52
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:44,400
on an earth that previously had not had life, is mostly a history problem.

53
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:47,080
What happened and when and where did it happen?

54
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:51,000
You could go a little bit beyond that and you might think of it as a problem of cause.

55
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,280
How did things happen and why?

56
00:04:54,280 --> 00:05:02,160
The argument that I want to make tonight is that we actually need to go further than that.

57
00:05:02,160 --> 00:05:07,200
The things that we've learned about the technical problems of when, where, and how have caused

58
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:11,760
us to realize that the nature of life is different from a lot of the patterns that we've traditionally

59
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:14,080
used to think about it.

60
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:18,760
The reason the origin of life problem is hard is that we do something in science that we

61
00:05:18,760 --> 00:05:20,520
also do in everyday life.

62
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:25,040
We put a big gap between the living things and the nonliving things.

63
00:05:25,040 --> 00:05:29,760
It's very difficult to see across that gap how something like life could have come from

64
00:05:29,760 --> 00:05:33,560
something that was not alive.

65
00:05:33,560 --> 00:05:36,920
So when we think about life, we often think about it in these terms.

66
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:38,480
Life is made of individuals.

67
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:39,600
They have agency.

68
00:05:39,600 --> 00:05:44,520
Maybe they have purpose or intentions that gives the biosphere direction.

69
00:05:44,520 --> 00:05:49,440
Even if the direction didn't come from the individuals, it comes from evolution.

70
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:55,280
Life is energetic, it's complex, and it's endlessly fascinating.

71
00:05:55,280 --> 00:05:56,280
Compare that to rocks.

72
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:57,280
What do rocks do?

73
00:05:57,280 --> 00:05:58,960
They just sit there.

74
00:05:58,960 --> 00:06:02,280
They've been around for billions of years.

75
00:06:02,280 --> 00:06:09,640
So what I want to argue to you tonight is that the conceptual gap between the nonliving

76
00:06:09,640 --> 00:06:15,960
world and living world is not real, or it's not where we have tried to place it in the

77
00:06:15,960 --> 00:06:16,960
past.

78
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:20,120
The nonliving world is very active.

79
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:24,520
It's richly structured in its activity, and the biosphere from the beginning all the way

80
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:29,760
to the present is embedded in detail in the structure of that chemical activity of the

81
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:31,680
rest of the planet.

82
00:06:31,680 --> 00:06:37,200
We haven't recognized the connections because our ways of looking have been too small or

83
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:38,800
they've been too short term.

84
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:43,920
They've been on the scale of a human life, or maybe we've looked in the wrong places.

85
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:49,680
But particularly in the last 30 years, things that we've learned in a variety of different

86
00:06:49,680 --> 00:06:55,040
disciplines are changing the way we ask those questions, and those are the things that cause

87
00:06:55,040 --> 00:07:00,920
us to reevaluate what we think the nature of life is and what we're trying to explain.

88
00:07:00,920 --> 00:07:04,840
So tonight, I want to cover four points.

89
00:07:04,840 --> 00:07:08,720
First of all, to understand the nature of life and the origin of life, you have to understand

90
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:14,520
its planetary context, and that context is what I will call a great arc of disequilibrium

91
00:07:14,520 --> 00:07:17,040
on the scale of the whole planet.

92
00:07:17,040 --> 00:07:22,760
Now even though that disequilibrium or stress runs through all of the systems on the planet,

93
00:07:22,760 --> 00:07:27,040
we can break it apart and we can make it comprehensible by doing something that geologists have done

94
00:07:27,040 --> 00:07:28,740
for more than a century.

95
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:33,640
We can divide the planet into geospheres, which are separate domains of states of matter

96
00:07:33,640 --> 00:07:37,120
and kinds of chemistry.

97
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:41,440
What we're looking for in the nature of life is actually at the level of the biosphere

98
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:48,760
as a whole, not at the level of its components, of species or organisms or sub-organism components.

99
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:52,640
The conclusion that I want to leave us with at the end of the night is that the biosphere

100
00:07:52,640 --> 00:07:54,760
is the fourth geosphere.

101
00:07:54,760 --> 00:07:59,200
We should understand it as a planetary subsystem, and we should understand the emergence of

102
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:05,320
life as a stage in planetary maturation akin to the stages that cause the other geospheres

103
00:08:05,320 --> 00:08:09,480
to be separated from each other.

104
00:08:09,480 --> 00:08:15,720
So in classical geology, a lifeless planet can have three geospheres.

105
00:08:15,720 --> 00:08:20,320
The lithosphere, from the word for rock, is the solid bulk.

106
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:24,360
On Earth, this is almost all of the matter and the mass of the planet.

107
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:30,160
The state of matter is solid, and the chemistry characteristic of the lithosphere is the chemistry

108
00:08:30,160 --> 00:08:34,720
of minerals and their changes.

109
00:08:34,720 --> 00:08:36,360
Second geosphere is the hydrosphere.

110
00:08:36,360 --> 00:08:39,360
This is all of the watery domains.

111
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:40,920
Water chemistry is very special.

112
00:08:40,920 --> 00:08:45,920
It's very restrictive, and as we've known forever, water chemistry is fundamental to

113
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:51,920
the nature of life, and it's in part important because of all the things you can't do in

114
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:57,840
water that you have to be distinctive that life does.

115
00:08:57,840 --> 00:09:00,680
The third non-living geosphere is the atmosphere.

116
00:09:00,680 --> 00:09:05,440
This is the gas phase because it's cool and because it's at low density.

117
00:09:05,440 --> 00:09:08,440
There are certain kinds of chemistry that are possible in the atmosphere that are not

118
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:10,680
possible other places.

119
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:15,280
Now the chemistry of the atmosphere is not actually very much like the chemistry of life,

120
00:09:15,280 --> 00:09:19,760
but it turns out that it's really important to the great arc of planetary disequilibrium

121
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:23,800
that will be central to our story.

122
00:09:23,800 --> 00:09:26,720
And the fourth is the biosphere.

123
00:09:26,720 --> 00:09:30,840
A lifeless planet will always have a lithosphere.

124
00:09:30,840 --> 00:09:35,320
If it has enough volatiles, as they're called, the liquids and gases, it can also have hydrospheres

125
00:09:35,320 --> 00:09:37,640
or atmospheres.

126
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:41,880
I want to look at the earth as it is, and everything that causes it to be different

127
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:45,560
from a planet that only had the three lifeless geospheres.

128
00:09:45,560 --> 00:09:49,240
And all of that difference is what I mean by the biosphere.

129
00:09:49,240 --> 00:09:52,360
So it is organisms, but not only organisms.

130
00:09:52,360 --> 00:09:57,080
It's all of their ecological relations, it's their history, and it's all the changes that

131
00:09:57,080 --> 00:10:01,960
they have collectively brought about in the rest of the planet throughout its history.

132
00:10:01,960 --> 00:10:05,920
So it's in the sum rather than in the components that we look for the nature of the living

133
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:10,320
state.

134
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:15,760
So I've said that there's not a gap that separates life conceptually from the rest of the earth,

135
00:10:15,760 --> 00:10:20,080
but certainly the biosphere is different from the non-living geospheres.

136
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:23,880
It's different in many ways, but if we had to choose one that's most important, here's

137
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:26,280
the one I would argue it is.

138
00:10:26,280 --> 00:10:31,240
For the other geospheres, the lithosphere, hydrosphere, and atmosphere, we can understand

139
00:10:31,240 --> 00:10:35,280
most of them in terms of their structure.

140
00:10:35,280 --> 00:10:42,480
For the biosphere, you can only really understand it as an organized state of activity.

141
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:47,600
In order to create an organized state of activity that goes beyond just structure, you have

142
00:10:47,600 --> 00:10:52,120
to be in a circumstance that physicists call far from equilibrium, and I'll explain to

143
00:10:52,120 --> 00:10:54,700
you in a minute what that means.

144
00:10:54,700 --> 00:10:58,920
The important thing is that the disequilibria we need to understand life are not something

145
00:10:58,920 --> 00:11:03,040
local, they're not local in space and they're not local in chemistry, they actually are

146
00:11:03,040 --> 00:11:07,200
built up on the scale of the whole planet.

147
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:11,600
So to give you a flavor for what is meant by near equilibrium or far from equilibrium,

148
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:15,560
I'll use something that's a little of an analogy, but it's an analogy that's mathematically

149
00:11:15,560 --> 00:11:17,600
faithful.

150
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:20,400
Near equilibrium is like the ripples on a pond.

151
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:25,840
There may be activity that's caused by disturbances, but most of what there is to understand can

152
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:32,520
be understood from the structure of the flat surface before you start.

153
00:11:32,520 --> 00:11:35,040
This is far from equilibrium.

154
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:40,480
Think of the biosphere as surfing on a continuously renewed wave of energy flow.

155
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:45,440
That energy flow is needed to keep it up where it is, it's needed to keep it organized.

156
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:51,360
Now it's been understood forever that life requires a flow of energy to maintain itself.

157
00:11:51,360 --> 00:11:57,000
But to say that something is required doesn't say that that's necessarily possible, it only

158
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,320
tells you what's impossible.

159
00:11:59,320 --> 00:12:01,480
Tonight I want to argue for something stronger.

160
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:07,100
I want to argue that the energy flows on earth brought the biosphere into existence.

161
00:12:07,100 --> 00:12:10,680
It's as if the wave had created the surfer.

162
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:16,620
So traditionally when we come at the problem of the origin of life from the habits of biology,

163
00:12:16,620 --> 00:12:20,480
we ask where is the surfer and what is the surfer like?

164
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:28,200
What I want to argue with here is that the right question should be where is the wave?

165
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:31,480
So the story of disequilibrium that makes sense of the origin of life doesn't start

166
00:12:31,480 --> 00:12:35,960
on the planet, it actually starts in the formation of the solar system.

167
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:40,440
Now when we look at the sun, the part we see is the photosphere.

168
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:41,440
Photosphere is relatively cool.

169
00:12:41,440 --> 00:12:45,040
It's only about 6,000 degrees Celsius, which is about the same temperature as the core

170
00:12:45,040 --> 00:12:46,200
of the earth.

171
00:12:46,200 --> 00:12:53,280
And it looks relatively smooth and flat like you see here, occasional sunspots.

172
00:12:53,280 --> 00:12:58,120
But if you were to look at the sun in the X-ray with a movie, you'd find a boiling cauldron

173
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:00,400
of magnetic fluid.

174
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:05,040
Because the sun produces heat and the heat needs to convect and because it's electrically

175
00:13:05,040 --> 00:13:10,640
conductive, you get loops of magnetism that boil up from the interior and whip plasma into

176
00:13:10,640 --> 00:13:13,360
the outer layers of the atmosphere.

177
00:13:13,360 --> 00:13:18,080
This action can cause the middle atmosphere of the sun, called the chromosphere, to go

178
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:20,440
up to 100,000 degrees or more.

179
00:13:20,440 --> 00:13:24,240
And it can elevate the corona to a million degrees or more.

180
00:13:24,240 --> 00:13:29,720
So plasma at 100,000 degrees emits extreme ultraviolet radiation, and at a million degrees

181
00:13:29,720 --> 00:13:34,080
or more it emits X-rays.

182
00:13:34,080 --> 00:13:38,920
So if you could look at the sun with a picture in the extreme UV in the X-ray, this is actually

183
00:13:38,920 --> 00:13:41,080
what you would find.

184
00:13:41,080 --> 00:13:46,520
The activity of a star like this is due to convection and the conductivity of the plasma,

185
00:13:46,520 --> 00:13:51,880
but also to the rotation, because this is a Coriolis effect, the same as hurricanes.

186
00:13:51,880 --> 00:13:56,480
And when stars are young when they're born, they rotate much faster and they spin down

187
00:13:56,480 --> 00:13:58,080
over time.

188
00:13:58,080 --> 00:14:03,120
So when the sun was young, all of this activity was actually more vigorous and more violent

189
00:14:03,120 --> 00:14:07,160
than it is today.

190
00:14:07,160 --> 00:14:13,080
Now that kind of hard radiation shapes planetary atmospheres, and in particular it drives them

191
00:14:13,080 --> 00:14:17,160
far out of equilibrium from the planet that they surround.

192
00:14:17,160 --> 00:14:21,120
So in particular, ultraviolet and above will break water.

193
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:26,440
Water is the H2O molecule where the Hs are white and the O is red, and it will separate

194
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:29,280
the hydrogen from the oxygen.

195
00:14:29,280 --> 00:14:33,400
Hydrogen is a very light element, and so anything will cause it to escape.

196
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:38,800
And the result is that you leave the oxygen behind.

197
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:42,960
This is actually a satellite photo of the Earth taken with a filter for the emission

198
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:45,200
lines that see hydrogen.

199
00:14:45,200 --> 00:14:50,160
And what you can see is that our planet is surrounded by a halo of hydrogen that's continually

200
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:54,040
escaping from it.

201
00:14:54,040 --> 00:14:56,960
That turns out to have major consequences.

202
00:14:56,960 --> 00:15:01,400
Because the rates of hydrogen loss that a star like our sun produces will remove a volume

203
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:05,880
of water comparable to the Earth's ocean in about a billion years.

204
00:15:05,880 --> 00:15:14,120
So if you were Venus, which is about our size but closer to the sun and a little bit warmer,

205
00:15:14,120 --> 00:15:19,240
or if you were Mars, which is smaller and has weaker gravity to hold elements, you would

206
00:15:19,320 --> 00:15:23,960
have wound up in the condition that they're in today, with no surface water, oxygen left

207
00:15:23,960 --> 00:15:27,520
behind that turns the dry surface a rusty red.

208
00:15:27,520 --> 00:15:30,880
In about four and a half billion years, the Earth may be in this condition, depending

209
00:15:30,880 --> 00:15:34,680
on how much water is on the inside, which is something we don't know.

210
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:39,520
But for the time being, the Earth is a very unusual planet in the solar system, and possibly

211
00:15:39,520 --> 00:15:42,560
more widely than that.

212
00:15:42,560 --> 00:15:47,440
But why does any of this matter to the origin of life?

213
00:15:47,480 --> 00:15:50,800
To answer that, you need to know a little bit of chemistry, but all you need to know

214
00:15:50,800 --> 00:15:54,200
is on this one slide.

215
00:15:54,200 --> 00:15:57,160
And it's intuitive, I promise.

216
00:15:57,160 --> 00:16:03,800
In the periodic table of the elements, we have many different kinds of animals.

217
00:16:03,800 --> 00:16:10,080
Some of the elements have a stronger what's called affinity for electrons than others.

218
00:16:10,080 --> 00:16:15,800
And in particular, important to our story, iron is very ready to give electrons away

219
00:16:15,960 --> 00:16:20,440
to many other elements, giving electrons away to something called reducing that, because

220
00:16:20,440 --> 00:16:23,080
electrons have a negative charge.

221
00:16:23,080 --> 00:16:28,880
At the opposite end, oxygen is very greedy and will steal electrons from many elements.

222
00:16:28,880 --> 00:16:33,360
And so you can see the transfer of electrons from iron to oxygen in the suites of minerals

223
00:16:33,360 --> 00:16:35,040
in the world.

224
00:16:35,040 --> 00:16:39,120
Iron metal, which mostly doesn't exist at the surface, has all of its electrons, and

225
00:16:39,120 --> 00:16:42,520
they're loosely bound, so they make a kind of a liquid, and that's why iron is silvery

226
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:44,880
and shiny and reflects light.

227
00:16:44,880 --> 00:16:49,720
If you bring in a little bit of oxygen, enough that there's one oxygen atom per iron atom,

228
00:16:49,720 --> 00:16:53,600
it will transfer two electrons to the oxygen, and we note that with a plus two on the iron

229
00:16:53,600 --> 00:16:58,520
